column22: Generate stands out to me as a place that allows data science to meet real entrepreneurship. Unlike other clubs focused on only building projects or competitions, Generate allows members’ work to empower startups and their founders.  What excites me most is the chance to apply and expand my skills in a setting where my work matters to real stakeholders, not just in the classroom or for a portfolio. Previous Generate projects have deeply inspired me, such as Ben Petrillo’s PlateMate. PlateMate exemplifies how Generate teams are able to not just extract analytical insights, but make impacts on stakeholders. Seeing these projects makes me think about where I could make a difference. For example, I’d love to enhance PlateMate’s analytics by leveraging my RAG experience, such as using textual data from menus and nutritional information to provide more concise dish performance insights.  My experience at myTickets building their own website’s chatbot from scratch has taught me the importance of collaborating creatively under time sensitive conditions to design practical data systems while maintaining clean products for users. Being able to spot where my skillset fits in, and the opportunity to collaborate with driven members are what makes me eager to join Generate.
column23: I’m confident in my abilities in LLM integration and RAG pipeline development. These are skills I’ve developed through all of academic projects, personal projects, and professional experience.  I’ve built a comprehensive retrieval system using Ollama, ChromaDB, and MongoDB, comparing multiple embedding models to optimize retrieval effectiveness, resulting in a RAG pipeline able to answer questions about academic class content. At myTickets, I worked as a Machine Learning Intern to prototype and build a multi-agent chatbot, allowing for ticket marketplace event recommendations through both natural language input, past user activity, and other user metadata. The skill I'm eager to develop is real time data infrastructure and streaming analytics. At myTickets, we realized without real time data infrastructure and streaming analytics by using technologies like Kafka, our recommendation system couldn’t adapt to our users preferences nearly as quickly. While I have a basic understanding of Kafka to enable real-time processing for pipelines, it’s something I’ve seen the importance of first hand, making me want to master Kafka and real time data infrastructure. Seeing the importance of incorporating new technologies, even if they are unfamiliar to me, is the driving factor that motivates me to learn new things and tackle challenges.
column24: Learning about algorithms, both in CS3000, and exploring them on my own time, was a transformative experience, shaping the way I view my work now. Previous to exploring algorithms and topics such as dynamic programming, computer science and data science felt like two separate domains with little in common, with one focused on optimizing code and programming, and the other on extracting data insights. However, studying algorithms has shown me how deeply interconnected the two are.  	Studying dynamic programming served as a great reminder of the power of breaking down problems into smaller, easier problems. On a more technical note, graph algorithms showed me the structure behind data retrieval, a topic I later used while building RAG pipelines in a different class. Learning about searching and sorting, breadth first search, depth first search, and the general topic of time complexity allowed me to see how algorithms and their efficiency can unlock new data analysis methodology.  	These algorithms topics all combined to allow me to think from different perspectives than before. Unlocking the computational, algorithmic approach to data problems has resulted in me building more efficient, scalable solutions and taught me how influential interdisciplinary studies can be.
column25: Working in both a technical professional role at a startup in myTickets, and a totally different professional role in retail operations at Nordstrom as a Logistics Processor has given me a unique dual perspective on what makes teams successful. I enjoyed a less structured role at myTickets, discussing and collaborating in a fast paced setting across interdisciplinary teams. On the other hand, at Nordstrom, I helped facilitate a tried and true inventory system amongst several store departments, whilst collaborating with each department manager to ensure store operations could continue.  In both roles, I’ve experienced how strong communication and support amongst group members are key to successful teams. Additionally, I’ve gained the understanding that great teams, like those at Generate, are built on a willingness to learn from one another, unite around a clear mission, and adapt to new challenges together. My contrasting experiences working with diverse groups of people gives me confidence that I can contribute to Generate and its teams not just on a technical level, but also with a clear communication and growth mentality that allows us to reach our end goal of creating valuable products for our startup partners.

column22: I am interested in joining Generate because, despite all the opportunities across the landscape of Northeastern, few offer true, real-world experience with the scale and magnitude of the projects that Generate takes on. The opportunity to work with real clients spanning across fields such as education and healthcare is something that not just something that excites me, but truly allows me to be a part of something that has a genuine impact on these industries during a time of my academic journey where opportunities are limited. I feel as though I have made my impact felt at Northeastern so far through my involvement with the South Asian cultural club UTSAV as Freshmen Representative, and now Cultural Chair. However, I feel it is also important that I use my technical and leadership skills to make my impact on the professional landscape here at Northeastern. The many teams and roles that compose Generate give the organization a “corporate-like” structure, which can prove to be invaluable going forward. As I can enter the CO-OP search and future job search, Generate can give me a distinct advantage that so few have in this field that continues to grow more and more competitive.
column23: The technical skill that I feel most confident in is my understanding of the programming language SQL and database design. Although I have only started exploring SQL this summer, I have quickly gained a strong understanding of the language and everything that it has to offer. Databases are the backbone of many web applications, including one that I am currently building. One thing that I would like to continue to build on would be my understanding of the many different Python libraries. I understand that a large portion of the data team for Generate operates through Python, and while I have a very strong understanding of it, I would like to expand my knowledge of the intricacies within Python. The thing that drives me the most to learn is the constant feeling that I don’t know enough. That feeling brings out the hunger to learn more, to keep pushing myself, and to keep competing in this field that is only getting more and more competitive. I have always had a slight feeling of imposter syndrome, so my immediate response to that has always been to push myself and work even harder.
column24: The biggest way that my past professional and extracurricular experiences have shaped me was as a leader. Leadership was not something I ever sought, nor was it something I was always comfortable with; however, it was a position that I was immediately thrust into as a 9th grader when I was named captain of the Shaker Varsity Tennis team. As a middle schooler and youngest state-qualifier, my prowess on the tennis court gained me all kinds of individual accolades; however, it contributed to very little team success. Previously, when I was a player, I got to observe the way previous captains went about leadership and dealing with situations. The biggest thing I took from them was that I should never ask anything of my teammates that I am not willing to do myself. In order to bring the best out of everyone around me, I needed to show that I was also willing to put in the hours myself. I truly believe that the best approach to leadership is leading by example and uplifting everyone around you. With this type of approach, not just overall performance, but the team environment also continues to grow stronger.
column25: Although he might not be a public figure, Professor Mark Fontenot has been very influential in my early journey into data science. Prior to this Summer, I had minimal data science background aside from the work that I had previously done in Python; however, this summer I was really able to explore data and database management through Professor Mark Fontenot. His teaching style was truly engaging and allowed me to understand the ways in which data can be used to be the backbone of projects. This understanding was also complemented by the work I had done in Seattle with Amazon Web Services and their cloud platform. Professor Fontenot helped strengthen my understanding of the cloud and Amazon Web Services platform to serve as a cloud container if I ever wish to scale my project that I am currently working on.
column26: I appreciate the consideration, thank you for your time.

column22: I am eager to join Generate because of its community-driven approach to product design and development. I’ve always been fascinated by the product development lifecycle and how entrepreneurial spirit brings the vision to life. Through my leadership roles with Scout and the Entrepreneurs Club, I’ve explored the various phases a product goes through from ideation to launch. Scout’s product design focus and E-club’s emphasis on ideation made me more curious about learning how data shapes a product at Generate. What draws me to Generate is its mission to not only build innovative products, but also to cultivate the growth of its members. I love that Generate gives students the chance to work directly with passionate and inspiring founders. We not only get to bring their vision to life, but also engage with their ideas and processes. In my experience organizing events for entrepreneurial focused clubs, I’ve met many founders who love working with students because of their creativity, energy, and new perspectives. The data scientist role is a perfect opportunity for me to grow my skills in developing data-driven insights in a collaborative and community oriented environment.
column23: One technical skill I am confident in is data visualization. Through both my coursework in data science and my data analysis internship with NUview, I’ve learned how important it is to choose the right visual to represent trends and prompt deeper questioning. At my co-op, I created waterfall charts to classify results from an order booking optimization model. These visualizations helped stakeholders understand complex outputs in a clear and meaningful way that sparks conversations about pain points and creating operational efficiencies. I’ve come to appreciate how visualizations do more than present data, they tell stories that encourage the development of actionable insights. A skill I would like to improve is data modeling. I want to deepen my understanding of how to minimize bias and prevent overfitting, so that I can build models that are more than just accurate, but are impactful towards real-world applications. What motivates me most is the excitement of continuous learning. I enjoy developing skills that not only help explain the past and present, but also enable us to predict outcomes in the future. Making more accurate assumptions about the future is very valuable for long-term growth and success.
column24: EDA is my favorite methodology because it consistently shapes how I approach problem-solving. When I first learned about EDA, I didn’t fully appreciate its importance until I began working with large datasets during my co-op. Especially in client-facing work, where accuracy and clarity are essential, EDA helps ensure that insights are both meaningful and aligned with the client’s goals. I found that datasets being used in industry often come from multiple sources and require joining databases with many fields. This process is often prone to inconsistency errors in naming conventions or data types. I’ve learned that rushing through EDA often results in longer completion times and misleading results. EDA helps uncover issues such as missing values, data type mismatches, and outliers early. What I value most about EDA is that it’s not just cleaning the data, you are also understanding the data throughout the process. By validating assumptions and exploring the structure of the dataset, I can make better decisions about which fields to use and validating my results. It saves time in the long run and is a foundational step for any modeling or analysis that follows.
column25: Though I haven’t been in Generate before, my professional and extracurricular experiences have helped me develop the collaborative, curious, and impact-driven qualities that I am excited to bring to the Generate team. During my co-op at Wayfair, I am working with the CastleGate Forwarding team that specializes in international shipping solutions for e-commerce. I am using Looker Studio and BigQuery connections in Google Sheets to build dashboards that track logistics processes, contract pipelines, and key business metrics. These dashboards support weekly business reviews and help streamline decision making. This experience continues to show me the significance of agile and iterative approaches in data analysis, where each version of a script or dashboards brings new insights and improvements. In my operations internship at The Community Preservation Corporation (CPC), I built and maintained a CRM system, which deepened my understanding of how data infrastructure supports long-term relationship management and business needs. In my data analysis internship with NUview and the Aspire Institute, I gained more experience with using raw Excel data to calculate engagement metrics that helped inform programming and long-term strategy with alumni. I’m excited to contribute these skills to Generate’s mission and collaborate with passionate members to build products that matter.

column16: I will be working part-time (10-15 hours a week).
column22: I’m particularly interested in joining Generate because of its wide reach and strong, diverse members. As a combined Computer Science and Cognitive Psychology major, I’m excited by how Generate brings together students from hardware, software, data, and design to collaborate on real-world problems. It’s one of the few organizations on campus where I feel like I can apply all facets of my academic background—whether through technical implementation or understanding user needs. I’ve seen the value of client collaboration firsthand through my internship at Leidos, where I worked directly with clients to understand and meet their needs. That experience taught me how important it is to balance technical skills with clear communication and adaptability. Beyond the work itself, I’m drawn to the community. I have friends who have stayed with Generate throughout their time at Northeastern not only because of the ability to learn, grow and work on new projects each semester, but because of the people in Generate and the community. I’m eager to contribute to and learn from such a driven, diverse team, and to continue growing both technically and personally in a space that values curiosity, impact, and collaboration.
column23: One technical skill I’m confident in is working with relational databases using SQL. I’ve used it extensively in both academic and professional settings to organize and query complex data structures. At Cambridge CARES, I used PostgreSQL to manage time series health data and connect it to a real-time mobile UI. This experience strengthened my ability to design scalable and efficient data pipelines.  A skill I’m eager to improve is my proficiency with Python for machine learning and predictive analytics. While I’ve used Python for data cleaning and basic modeling, I want to deepen my understanding of advanced techniques and libraries. I’m especially interested in applying these tools to real-world data science problems.  What motivates me to keep learning is the desire to build innovative, high-impact solutions. At Leidos, I’m currently working on adapting large language models to detect and mitigate manipulation in digital environments. Tackling this challenge has shown me how quickly the field evolves—and how important it is to stay on top of the latest tools and research. I’m excited by the chance to keep growing so I can contribute meaningfully to cutting-edge, socially relevant projects.
column24: One data science methodology I find really interesting is neural networks—especially recurrent neural networks (RNNs), which are often used to model sequences like language or time-based data. As someone studying both Computer Science and Cognitive Psychology, I’m drawn to how these models mirror some aspects of human cognition, like memory and pattern recognition over time.  What I appreciate most about neural networks is how they evolve through feedback—constantly tuning and improving, much like how people learn through experience. That’s shaped the way I approach problem-solving: I try to think beyond just technical accuracy and consider how a system might align with how humans think, interact, and make decisions.  At Leidos, I’ve been working on projects involving large language models and behavioral modeling, and this idea of iteratively learning and improving has been central. Neural networks have pushed me to stay curious and open—to experiment, adjust, and keep asking questions. They remind me that data science isn’t just about building something that works—it’s about building something that adapts and grows, just like the people using it.
column25: As a Computer Science and Cognitive Psychology major, I’ve explored diverse extracurriculars and professional experiences to blend my technical and interpersonal skills. Early on, I engaged in software development, tutoring, and research, each teaching me valuable lessons: building websites sharpened my collaboration and communication skills, tutoring deepened my empathy by seeing problems from others’ perspectives, and research emphasized teamwork and structure.  Last spring, I co-oped at Cambridge CARES in Singapore, developing a mobile app that tracks real-time health data. This role enhanced my software and data skills, working with time series data and databases, while also teaching me independence and cultural adaptability.  Currently, I’m interning at Leidos, where I work on data modeling and collaborate directly with clients like Intel to evaluate AI PC usability and emotional intelligence. This experience has strengthened my ability to communicate proactively and balance technical work with client needs.  Though my journey has been non-linear, it’s taught me the importance of empathy and clear communication alongside technical expertise—qualities I’m eager to bring as a data scientist at Generate.

column22: My co-op experience as a data engineer showed me how impactful real-world projects can be for both personal growth and solving real problems. Generate’s mission of “empowering driven students through product development” resonates with me. Unlike other orgs on campus that focus on practice projects, Generate delivers actual solutions to real stakeholders allowing me to build solutions that have a genuine impact. A byproduct of creating such solutions is the satisfaction of seeing my work create measurable impact. The new data branch is also an exciting opportunity as data members get to help shape the direction of the branch. I believe my end-to-end data pipeline experience (integrating Salesforce and Snowflake into automated dashboards) positions me to contribute immediately while learning from Generate’s proven client delivery. The collaborative, feedback-driven approach particularly appeals to me as my experience working with stakeholders has taught me that the best data solutions come from understanding the context of your work, not just the technical implementation. I’m excited to bring my technical experience while growing alongside team members from different perspectives.
column23: A technical skill I have developed and am confident in is end-to-end data solution design. During my co-op, I worked as a data engineer at Northeastern's College of Arts, Media, and Design. Here we found a trend of declining co-op placement rates since the Covid-19 pandemic. As a result, my team found the need for analyzing placed student resumes to pinpoint the skills and experiences that were pivotal in getting placed. In the past, this would be a manual process requiring tens of hours to review hundreds of resumes, however, I was able to use Google's Gemini API to create a workflow which would automate this process. My pipeline automated four stages: data identification, resume extraction from NUWorks, Gemini-powered analysis, and roadmap visualization. The results of this project were highly actionable roadmaps that were distributed to the 2000+ students within the college. One technical skill I would like to learn/improve is MLOps and scalable model deployment. The resume review project gained interest from other colleges within Northeastern, but I lacked the infrastructure knowledge to easily scale the Gemini workflow across multiple institutions. I'm motivated to learn because I see the impact my work can have. My resume project directly helped 2000+ students better map their career paths. I'm also motivated because I enjoy understanding how complex systems work - I’m currently reading "Why Machines Learn by Anil Ananthaswamy" to understand ML foundations and build connections between technical implementations and their real-life counterparts. I am genuinely excited about applying the skills that I acquire to tackle challenges that I haven’t solved before.
column24: My favorite influential figure in the data science field has to be Warren McCulloch. I recently read about McCulloch and Walter Pitts’ work regarding artificial neural networks. Their work back in 1943 laid the groundwork for AI/ML, a field I am deeply interested in understanding. McCulloch and Pitts took the logic of a real neuron and used mathematics to create an artificial neuron that could perform logical operations. This approach was ground-breaking at the time, but had its limitations, requiring hand calculations to work. Nowadays, through other scientists that built upon McCulloch’s work, we have artificial intelligence and machine learning. Their systematic approach of breaking down complex biological processes into simple mathematical components helped me understand how to solve problems better and I was even able to apply it to my current work. 	Currently, as part of an internship at Rigr.ai, an AI company working with law enforcement, I’m developing an NLP model that can predict user location based on their texts. This works by identifying language markers within user texts and determining user location from these markers. The technical challenge involves training models to recognize the subtle geographical language variations while maintaining accuracy across text sources. The model assists law enforcement in child safety investigations by providing location insights for more effective resource allocation. The architecture follows McCulloch-Pitt's thinking: simple processing units linked together to create sophisticated outcomes.
column25: My professional and extracurricular experiences have shaped me into someone who values the impact and importance of my work in addition to technical detail. My co-op as a data engineer at Northeastern's College of Arts, Media, and Design had me working with data to help students. When we discovered declining co-op placement rates post-COVID, rather than diving straight into technical details, I first focused on understanding the problem. Working directly with coordinators and hearing from students experiencing these challenges, I created an automated resume analysis workflow that helped 2000+ students better understand their career paths. This collaboration taught me the importance of understanding problems from the source—the people actually experiencing them. Seeing my work have such a positive impact was incredibly rewarding and taught me that meaningful solutions require both understanding root causes and working systematically with diverse stakeholders to break complex challenges into manageable components. My extracurricular activities reinforced these values. Working with NUView to analyze Aspire Institute's alumni newsletter performance taught me how data-driven recommendations help organizations better serve their communities—a lesson I reinforced through Biokind Analytics, analyzing patient quality of life data for the Ellie Fund's breast cancer support services. Each experience has reinforced my belief that technology should create meaningful impact. This mindset is exactly what I want to bring to Generate's client-centered approach to product development!

column17: I heard about this application through friends who are also applying.
column22: While many organizations may offer opportunities to develop technical skills, Generate’s emphasis on client-driven projects that solve genuine problems really attracts me. Of course, it is important to try and learn different skills as much as you can, I find it especially important to hone those skills through applied workshops or projects. I’ve always found it more interesting to master a topic through solving a problem as opposed to reading a book or solving a tedious workset. I’ve taken a look at the various projects that those at Generate have produced in the past, and grow eager. It is clear that Generate is the home of driven, focused students ready to make an impact on the world.  Data science and AI has grown and evolved at an exponential rate over the last few years. With startups rising at every corner of the world, I’m certain there are countless clients in Boston ready to work with a motivated group of students. And so, I grow excited thinking of the opportunity of working with talented peers on new products this year in the new data science branch.
column23: When applying to colleges, I hunted for buzzwords taht would make my application stand out. That led me to neural networks. The more I learned, the more fascinated I became (what especially caught my attention was how they are known as “black boxes,” like what do you mean we may never know all of what goes on in our models). Well, as I grew more adept in data science and machine learning I decided to take on a more challenging project. CNNs are a type of deep learning algorithm that are especially effective with images. They learn to recognize complex patterns in data through convolutional and pooling layers through identifying features (edges, shapes, etc.). In my project, LungScan, I successfully implemented a custom CNN architecture that classifies histopathological scans of lung and colon tissues into five categories. My model achieved 95% accuracy on my test set. I feel that I’ve brought myself to a point where I’m fairly confident in my skill with implementing CNNs. One thing I’d like to improve upon is NLP. While we did learn basic NLP techniques in DS2500, I want to expand upon my skills in sentiment or text analysis. This would allow me to be able to tackle a broader range of problems.   My motivation to learn different data science and machine learning techniques / skills comes from a place of curiosity. AI has been growing at a rate that we never could have expected, and it shows no signs of slowing down. I want to keep up the pace with it, and I want to be at the forefront of it. I find the ins and outs of AI ever fascinating, and am fueled by the practical theory behind it and the application of it.
column24: Although he isn’t necessarily a data scientist nor is his content specifically related to data science, Grant Sanderson - the creator of the 3Blue1Brown YouTube channel - has been a major influence on my approach to data science. 3Blue1Brown is known for taking abstract mathematical concepts and demonstrating them in clear, intuitive ways. His animations have allowed me to wrap my head around concepts I struggled with. For example, his 8 video series on neural networks took my understanding to a different level. Being able to visualize how the model itself thinks and operates changed the way I approached developing my models. This mindset of visualizing before implementing continues to help my understanding of various topics and helps my ability to communicate different skills I’d learned. While I tend to use his videos more for math nowadays, I still look to visualize the models’ tendencies prior to developing it.
column25: This last semester, I participated as a mentor in ProjectML where I guided a group of 6 participants through a 3-week online program focused on building our participants a foundation in machine learning. Twice a week, I would guide students through data preprocessing techniques, different algorithms, ways to evaluate our models, etc. I didn’t immediately realize it, but by teaching my peers, I was able to better learn those topics myself.  After I was done teaching them the basics, I encouraged each of my students to choose their own dataset and work on it. I was there to guide them as they got stuck, but I really encouraged them to tackle their own obstacles before coming for assistance (also to not just use AI for the whole thing). One of my students kept seeing unexpected results from his model. Initially, I assumed we needed to change the model itself, but after trial and error, we found that the problem wasn’t actually with the model. The student had chosen a dataset about sentiment regarding COVID-19. He’d mapped his data to three different labels: “positive,” “negative,” and “neutral,” and the total count in ”neutral” was significantly fewer than in “negative” and “positive.” This skewed his results greatly. By taking a step back and deciding what we really wanted our model to predict (in this case positive and negative sentiments, not neutral) we were able to overcome the problem by dropping the “neutral” column.  This experience of mentoring fellow students humbled me, and taught me different ways to approach the problem. It is important to look at all the different facets of the problem as opposed to focusing on just one possible one.

column22: Even before stepping on campus, I’ve been looking for ways to maximize my college experience from day one. While browsing clubs on Instagram this summer, Generate immediately stood out with the kind of work that was being done: real projects, real clients, and real impact. The new data team especially caught my eye because it lines up perfectly with what I want to do in college. There are a lot of clubs that help students grow, but Generate is different because it mirrors the kind of environment I eventually want to work in: cross-functional, fast-paced, and filled with people who are excited to build cool things. I’ve been learning data science independently this summer out of pure interest, but I know self-learning can only take me so far. I’m looking to take that next step by contributing to real projects, learning from others, and being pushed outside my comfort zone. Generate’s product-focused, collaborative environment is exactly what I’m looking for. Even as a freshman, I’m ready to contribute, absorb knowledge quickly, and grow alongside others who are serious about data and tech. I want to start building from day one, and Generate feels like the best place to do that.
column23: One technical skill I’ve developed this summer is SQL. I’ve been practicing how to write queries, create tables, and understand how structured data is stored and accessed. It’s helped me better understand how data flows behind the scenes, especially during a small personal project where I built a system that takes input of what’s in my fridge and outputs recipe ideas based on what I could make at home. That project also made me realize how important Python is when working with data pipelines and logic. While I’ve touched Python a bit, I still have a long way to go, especially when it comes to using data-focused libraries like pandas. I’d love to improve in that area by working on real projects in a collaborative setting, where I can both contribute and learn from others. What motivates me most is the satisfaction of figuring something out after struggling with it. I enjoy problem-solving, even if it means making mistakes along the way. That “aha” moment after fixing a bug for the first time is what keeps me going. I also like the idea of building things that are useful or interesting to others. It makes the challenge feel worth it.
column24: One of my favorite data science concepts is linear regression. It was the first algorithm I truly understood, and it helped me realize how simple tools can uncover valuable insights from data. I liked how it didn’t rely on anything flashy. It just drew a straight line through points and made a prediction based on that. That simplicity made data feel less intimidating and more approachable. Learning linear regression shaped how I think about problem-solving. It taught me that you don’t always need complex models or advanced techniques to get value out of data. What matters more is understanding the context and using the right tool for the job. That mindset stuck with me, especially during my fridge recipe recommender project. I tried not to overcomplicate things and instead focused on logic and structure first. As I continue learning, I try to build from that foundation: understanding the “why” behind each method, not just how to use it. I want to be able to make decisions that are both technically sound and practically useful, and linear regression was the first step in showing me how to think that way.
column25: My past experiences have shaped how I learn, lead, and build. This summer, I worked on building a shoe recommendation project using AI. I initially had no clue how to build it, so I vibe-coded my way through while figuring out how to structure user data, use the GPT-4 API, and connect feedback to recommendation outputs. It gave me a better understanding of how data flows through a system. In high school, I was a project lead and PR director in our coding club, where I led internal tech projects and handled outreach. My favorite experience was competing in a NYC high school hackathon, where my team built a game using Python. I worked on the backend logic that tracked health, hits, and player status, and we made it to the top 5. These experiences showed me how much I enjoy working on real projects and figuring things out as I go. I like being part of a team, especially when everyone brings different skills to the table. I’m excited to take that to the next level at Generate where I can keep building, but in a more structured, product-focused environment with people who are just as driven.
column26: As a freshman, I know I’m early in my journey, but I really believe I can thrive in Generate. Even if I’m not selected, I’d love to stay involved by shadowing, learning from members, or attending events.

column22: As a young Data Science & Finance major, I am drawn to Generate not only for its support in exploring different interests that align with my studies, but also for its strong focus on entrepreneurship. From watching Shark Tank as a kid to participating in a summer program at Babson College, I have always been inspired by the type of growth that entrepreneurship sparks. Entrepreneurship fosters a growth mindset that transcends technical expertise, and I am particularly drawn to Generate for their emphasis on growth and developing leaders in product development. From helping startups build their products from the ground up to assisting clients scale their ventures, this process involves an entrepreneurial mindset that thrives on empathy, adaptability, and innovative thinking. Generate offers the ideal environment for me to take on challenges that will sharpen my leadership abilities and inspire innovation. Being involved in these early-stage challenges is invaluable as it pushes me to continuously learn and grow. By aligning with Generate’s mission, I hope to not only hone my analytical skills but also make meaningful contributions to one day become a leader in the field of data science.
column23: I am confident in my ability to analyze and visualize datasets using libraries in Python. In one project, I created word clouds from the top ten most active X/Twitter users on conversations about voice phishing and scam calls. Another project involved analyzing travel and tourism in the UK, where I uncovered key travel trends using line plots and box and whisker plots. I used bar carts to visualize the top countries UK residents like to visit and spend the most money at, doing the same analysis for overseas residents as well. Additionally, I worked with a moderation dataset from Maston where I built a similarity network to visualize moderation instances across the platform, color-coded by their respective moderation reason. While I am confident in my ability to work with Python, I am eager to learn SQL. I will be taking Introduction to Databases next semester, where I will be taught SQL. I’m excited to pick up this essential tool as efficiently managing large databases is very useful in data analysis. What motivates me to learn new things is my dislike for stagnation. The idea of staying the same person forever doesn’t resonate with me; I’m always looking to learn new skills and explore opportunities. This driven mindset is what pushes me to continuously improve and take on challenges.
column24: One of my favorite data science methodologies is sentiment analysis. This technique can take text data and compute its sentiment score—whether it’s positive, negative, or neutral. This tool has been very helpful in several of my projects. In my project where I analyzed conversations about voice phishing and scam calls, I used sentiment analysis to gauge public perception. I find it fascinating how human emotions and behavior can be understood by just applying natural language processing to real-world data.
column25: While I haven’t been involved with Generate yet, my experiences have shaped me into a highly driven individual. My most recent occupation was doing door-to-door sales, which I would’ve never imagined myself doing. I pushed myself out of my comfort zone, and I was able to develop many useful skills. I learned that sales is in conversation. While a physical product may not be sold, an idea might be. I have become a better active listener. Instead of listening to reply, I listen to understand. By being more present in conversations, I have been better at understanding individuals and picking up on body signals. Additionally, when I was having bad luck at work, I was forced to learn how to be adaptable. I had to understand what worked and what didn’t work for different neighborhoods. “Was it my icebreaker that was off, or did I not build enough value in the product?” I learned how to reflect on my performance and pick apart the positives and the work-ons.

column22: What draws me to Generate is how closely it mirrors the real world. There are teams for management, data, software, hardware, finance, marketing, and more, all working together like in an actual company. I think that’s incredibly valuable, because in real projects, code is just one part of the process. From past experience, I’ve learned that focusing only on development isn’t enough because there are so many other moving parts that can make or break a project. I really want to see how all the teams interact, how decisions are made and how ideas go from concept to execution. That kind of exposure is rare and hard to get in a classroom setting. And honestly, being around passionate, talented people who are building cool things is the kind of environment I’m looking for. I’ve seen posts on Instagram of community events and it feels like a team that works hard, and knows how to have fun, and I’d really want to be part of it.
column23: One technical skill I’ve developed and feel confident in is web scraping. I used to do it a lot for personal projects just because I found it interesting to collect data from different websites. I liked figuring out how the site loads content, finding the right patterns in the HTML, and writing scripts using BeautifulSoup and Selenium to extract what I needed. At one point, I wanted to build my own large database of information for science olympiads with all problems, solutions, and files from all around the world. Back in school, I dreamed of going to IPhO (didn’t work out), so I just wanted to make something that could help future students access everything in one place. Databases are really something I want to get better at. I know the basics of SQL and how to connect and query, but I’d like to get better at designing, managing, and editing more complex databases. What motivates me to learn is pretty simple. I don’t want to live life with regrets. A while ago, I promised myself that I want to look back one day and feel proud of what I’ve done, and happy with how I got there.
column24: One of the most interesting data science concepts I’ve explored is Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs). I came across them while working on my Virtual Touch project, where I was building a gesture-based control system using a regular webcam. At first, I used color detection and contour tracking to detect hands, but the system broke easily with different lighting or slight changes in hand shape. I started looking into CNNs to solve this. I didn’t manage to fully integrate one, but learning how they extract features from images layer by layer helped me rethink my approach. Instead of manually tuning every rule, I began focusing on how to design systems that can generalize better from input data. It also pushed me to learn more about training models, preprocessing data, and how small visual details can change everything.
column25: I’ve been seriously trying to get into software engineering for less than a year. I’ve learned a lot and made solid progress, but I don’t feel like it’s enough to write a deep story about yet. So instead, I want to talk about something that’s been with me much longer: music. I’ve been playing guitar for the last five years, and other instruments before that. It’s always been a part of my life, so I tried to post my playing online as I thought I’m a solid player. But it was such a humbling experience. Not because people’d say something bad, but because I started hearing every tiny mistake I used to ignore. Notes slightly off, rhythm not quite right. I’d spend hours replaying the same few seconds, trying to make it sound clean. It was frustrating, but it taught me a lot. I realized real growth happens in the small details, and that doing something “well enough” is not the same as doing it right. That mindset is now what I’m trying to apply to all parts of my life. Not always successful, but well, I guess that’s how people grow.

column10: Data Science and Business Administration (Finance concentration)
column22: I want to join Generate because it bridges the gap between classroom learning and real-world development. Beyond the projects, what excites me most is the friendly and creative environment I’ve seen through current members, and Generate social media platforms. I look forward to building friendships outside of the classroom with people who share my passion for technology. I also hope to gain guidance from mentors in Generate, and in the future, I hope to mentor others and help them grow as well.
column23: A technical skill I’m confident in is data visualization. I quickly adapt to new libraries and build on those that I already use. Additionally, my business administration combined major has helped me excel (no pun intended) in statistics and probability concepts that I use hand in hand with data visualization. I will be taking a graduate course CS5800 (Algorithms) this fall, which I believe will strengthen my abilities and help me thrive in the Generate program. Surrounding myself with other like-minded generate members who have accomplished so much upon joining this group gives me the motivation to learn new things and take on challenges. As an extremely motivated person myself, I believe exposure to all opportunities, whether they turn out to be an interest of mine or not, helps give me the insight I need to make better decisions in the future.
column24: My favorite influential figure in the field is Daliana Liu, a former Amazon Senior Data Scientist with seven years of experience in machine learning and data science. I discovered her podcast on Spotify last year, and although she wasn’t the most well-known figure, her motivation and drive to shape her career inspired me to keep listening. Daliana now works in coaching and content creation, sharing what she learned from navigating her career as a data scientist. She interviews data scientists, professors, CEOs, researchers, and so much more. My favorite episodes feature professors whose perspectives have influenced the courses I’ve taken and plan to take, as well as my point of view on certain career choices and pathways I plan to pursue. I also admire that she was director of her college drama club while earning her BS in Mathematics. As a former competitive dancer, singer, and actor, I relate to her. I believe “theater kids” bring unique experiences that benefit our professional lives. Learning to accept constructive criticism and direction from a young age has taught me to collaborate and approach feedback with grace and an open mind.
column25: My extracurriculars and jobs have shaped my skills and mindset. In high school, I balanced sports, after-school clubs, volunteering, and two jobs, one in retail and one in food service, which taught me motivation, balance, and patience skills. I’ve continued both jobs through college, where I carried that patience I earned into my first year at Northeastern. I chose to go at my own pace, focusing on time management and figuring out what I wanted to accomplish during my years at school. This decision ultimately led me to want to join Generate. Over the past year, joining my sorority Kappa Delta and participating in religious clubs, which I hadn’t originally planned, showed me the value of stepping outside my comfort zone. In doing so, I discovered I’m optimistic, collaborative, and eager to help others. I want to join a group that contributes to my community and supports those around me, and I believe Generate is that group for me.
column26: Thank you for considering my application!

column22: Two things that I believe Generate does better than anyone at Northeastern: Client-based and professional style, and fostering an interdisciplinary environment. Generate's client-focused approach excites me most. Working on projects with real-world implications is rare, especially while taking classes and not on co-op. Compared to the clubs I’m currently in, I’m missing the broader impact in my work. Generate's combination of real client challenges and collaborative teamwork is exactly the kind of environment I want to be a part of. Many people forget Generate is more than just a computer science club, yet this is one of the most attractive parts of the club for me. Though I love my fellow CS majors, I believe working alongside members focused on the business side of things, people working to build real hardware, and creative minds focused on promoting Generate would broaden my perspective and make me a better problem-solver.
column23: I'm most confident in my ability to quickly learn new technologies. As a rising sophomore, I've embraced every chance to work with new technologies. This varied exposure to diverse tech stacks has made learning routine. At Generate, I’m sure I won’t be 100% familiar with everything I would work with, and that excites me. Beyond this, I want to learn and improve my system design and architecture skills in collaborative settings. While I’m no stranger to building and working in teams, shipping a large scale production-grade system from scratch is something I can definitely learn from. Generate would be ideal for working in an industry-adjacent setting, as I’d collaborate with my team and really understand the inner workings of such a large scale project. Designing something huge from scratch is a learning experience I am ecstatic to take advantage of as I progress in my career. What motivates me is that feeling when it clicks, and something I made is working. It would only get better at Generate, seeing my hard work translate into functional solutions that create real impact for clients.
column24: One methodology that changed how I approach my work is text vectorization, specifically TF-IDF. I first learned about it from a friend using it for an NLP project, and it opened up a new world of projects I could tackle. Before TF-IDF, I limited myself to projects with quantitative data, and didn't step into anything categorical. When I realized we could take categorical data and create meaningful numerical representations, I was surprised. I realized I could have employed this within my SHIELD project to improve analysis of threats. However, since I was satisfied with that project, I turned my attention to a new project I'm working on that uses RAG and text vectorization to provide accurate nutritional information for my gym journey. While I'm in the early stages, it's exciting to see how much TF-IDF enables. Knowledge in this methodology has been valuable beyond my own projects. I was able to help a friend who was having trouble analyzing unpredictable categorical responses in survey data. The concept of keeping track of a word's significance in an accurate numerical representation is extremely interesting, and is now my first instinct when I encounter messy data.
column25: Though I haven't been in Generate before, joining has been a huge goal since meeting upperclassmen who excited me about the growth and learning opportunities here. While not in Generate, I’ve made sure to keep myself involved within our campus community to ensure I keep learning in (and out of) the tech space. As a software developer at TedXNortheasternU, I collaborate with our Tech team to build new components and features using React for our website. Additionally, we work on integrating Sanity to manage our content dynamically. Through TedX, I’ve been able to grow technically while also getting introduced to a team setting of college students. Furthermore, my research assistant position at the Movement Neuroscience Lab (MNL) has pushed me to work with unfamiliar technologies like C# and Unity, forcing me to adapt and find comfort in new waters. My strength in teamwork stems from my internship at WRE, where I was exposed to an Agile environment in a professional setting, allowing me to take those skills and apply them here in a college environment as well. Generate would serve as the perfect next-step, allowing me to contribute what I’ve gained, while continuing to learn outside my comfort zone.

column22: When I think about what I want most out of my college experience, it’s not just the roles I take on, but the memories and people I share them with. That’s what draws me to Generate. I’ve heard so much about how strong the community is, not just professionally, but socially. The idea of being part of a group where I can sit down for lunch with people who get excited about the same things I do, show up to events together, and build real friendships while working on meaningful projects. That’s exactly the environment I want to be in.   As someone applying for the data science team, I’m excited to contribute by analyzing data, building models, and uncovering insights that can help Generate make smarter, more informed decisions. I look forward to working on projects that improve how the organization understands its impact and optimizes its resources. I see this role as a chance to grow my technical skills while supporting a team and community I respect.   Generate’s value that stands out most to me is intentionality. I admire how Generate doesn’t just do things to check a box, but approaches every task with purpose and thoughtfulness. That mindset, combined with the kindness and inclusivity I’ve heard so much about, makes Generate feel like a place where I can grow both professionally and personally.
column23: One technical skill I feel confident in is writing clean, well-organized Java code. I’ve spent a lot of time learning how to structure my programs in a way that’s modular and maintainable, and I really enjoy the logic behind object-oriented design. It’s the kind of work that feels satisfying when everything fits together just right.   Something I’m less confident in is web development. I recently built my first full website and taught myself JavaScript, TailwindCSS, and a bit of backend with Flask. It was a fun challenge, but I know I’m still early in that journey. There’s so much more I want to learn, especially when it comes to building dynamic, user-friendly interfaces.   What motivates me most is the feeling of turning something unfamiliar into something I understand and then actually getting to use it to build things that work. I like pushing myself out of my comfort zone, especially when I know the skills I’m gaining will help me contribute more to a team. Plus, nothing beats the moment when something finally runs after hours of trial and error.
column24: One of my favorite algorithms is decision trees because they break down complicated problems into simple yes-or-no questions, kind of like how I approach decisions in real life. It actually reminds me of the Prisoner’s Dilemma we studied in microeconomics, where each choice depends on what you think the other person will do. Both require thinking step-by-step and anticipating different outcomes.   When I’m working on a project, whether it’s debugging code or organizing data workflows, I try to break the problem down into smaller pieces, just like a decision tree. For example, if something isn’t working, I ask myself questions like “Is this data clean?” or “Did this function run correctly?” Each answer guides me toward the next step. This way of thinking helps me stay organized and logical, and it also makes it easier to explain my process to teammates. It’s become a practical framework that shapes how I solve problems every day.
column25: While I haven’t been in Generate yet, a lot of my growth has come from building things with people who care just as much as I do. Whether that’s designing a GUI for a marine robot in Northeastern Robotics or replacing an international nonprofit’s paper system with a clean Airtable dashboard. Each project taught me how to problem-solve in real-world contexts, communicate with both tech and non-tech people, and stay calm when things go wrong.   But beyond the code, what’s helped me grow the most is the people like the mentors, teammates, friends who made those experiences feel collaborative, not transactional. That’s what draws me to Generate. I want to build meaningful projects with people I can also grab a bagel with after a late-night bug fix. Growth to me is technical and personal, and I’ve heard Generate offers both in one very cool, very kind package.

column22: I’m excited to join Generate because it offers the opportunity to find real solutions in a collaborative environment. As a CS/Math major, I’m always looking for ways to apply technical skills to solve practical problems, and Generate’s mission aligns perfectly with that. In a past co-op, I worked on internal tools used by investment analysts and collaborated directly with them (the end users) to understand their needs. That experience showed me how impactful it is to build intentionally and iterate based on real feedback, which I appreciate is a shared value in Generate. What sets Generate apart is the emphasis on teamwork and culture. From my own past experience, I found it to be a space where people genuinely care about their work and each other, and that kind of environment pushes me to grow and learn which is an experience that I really value.
column23: One technical skill I’ve developed and feel confident in is building data-driven backend tools (specifically in Python). During my past co-op at Wellington, I designed tools to automate data quality reporting and extend visualization dashboards in Tableau. I enjoyed the challenge of working directly with data and iterating based on user feedback to make meaningful & impactful improvements. One area I’m actively looking to improve is working with machine learning models in production. I’ve studied the theory and done some personal experimentation based on classwork, but I’m excited to deepen my understanding of how to build and deploy ML systems.
column24: One of my favorite data science methodologies is data visualization, as a part of the analytical process instead of just the final step. Whether I’m exploring patterns or communicating insights, visualizations help make data clearer, more accessible, and ultimately more impactful in a way that is not always as effectively communicated through words. During my co-op at Wellington, I extended Tableau dashboards used by investment professionals, where clarity and precision were critical. These experiences taught me that not only do strong visualizations display information, but importantly, they tell a story, highlight what matters, and help users make important decisions. Visualization has shaped the way I approach problem-solving, as I now think more about how others will interpret and use what I build.
column25: As a Business Analyst on the Data Team in Fall ’23, I started internal dashboards that helped some of the hardware team track the materials cost/quantity. It was a great opportunity to apply both technical and analytical skills by cleaning and analyzing data, and building dashboards that made information more accessible. What made the experience especially meaningful was the culture. I found that Generate fosters a space where everyone is encouraged to take ownership while still learning from each other. column22: I'm drawn to Generate because it bridges the gap between student development and real-world impact. Never having the chance to directly own or build the user-facing solution. What excites me most about Generate is the opportunity to be at the forefront of product development, contributing to tangible outcomes that real startups and businesses rely on. I'd also like to add that seeing all the cool things students have build at the end of semester Generate showcases has been a big awe factor about this club!
column23: One technical skill I’m confident in is working with data; whether that’s transforming large datasets, building visualizations, or writing SQL queries. I enjoy making data easier to understand and consolidating to make it more useful for real decisions. A skill I’d love to improve is LLM prompting and learning how to work better with AI models. Since AI is becoming such a big part of the tech world, it makes sense to learn how to use it effectively instead of avoiding it. What motivates me to learn new things is the idea that there’s always a better or more creative way to solve a problem. I like having a growth mindset and trying things that push me outside of what I already know. Taking on new challenges gives me a broader set of experiences and helps me become a stronger and more adaptable builder.
column24: One of my favorite concepts in data science is search algorithm (binary search, BFS, and DFS). I was fun learning them in CS3000, mostly because they were one of the few topics that actually made sense right away. Beyond just being fun, they are pretty applicable to everyday life. I remember joking with my friends on whether or not to use BFS or DFS for something completely non CS related. These algorithms have stuck with me because they can be a solution to solving things applicable to real life. Even outside of class, they’ve helped me approach things like research or exploring new ideas with a little more structure.
column25: Having worked in both big tech and finance, I’ve developed a strong understanding of these environments. While their core goals are similar, the processes they use to reach them differ. Moving from finance to tech was a big culture shock because tech is more flexible and lenient as long as you get your work done. The “work hard, play hard” mindset really resonates with me and has inspired me to focus more on computer science than finance. Knowing both sides gives me a well-rounded view of what it takes for a business to succeed. Outside of work, I enjoy creative activities like painting, drawing, journaling, and reading, though I admit I spend some time on social media too. Growing up involved in the art world taught me the value of personal expression, which I try to bring into my academic and professional work. Ultimately, creativity is something I truly enjoy and value.

column22: Though interests and plans change over time, as of now, I am deeply interested in the world of startups and have a love for the creative process that goes into making something. The premise of Generate offers the perfect environment to gain real startup experience. In my opinion, the best way to learn is by doing, and after hearing that the Data team will be completely client-facing this year, I know that it will offer opportunities that align with my goals far more so than many of the clubs on campus can offer. Having researched the previous projects listed on Generate’s website, I think it’s amazing that the work you do as a student makes a real impact on companies. Additionally, I noticed that some of the founders that Generate works with are Northeastern alumni, which offers another cool opportunity to work directly with people who were in the same shoes I’m in now. Having the ability to see how they are utilizing their Northeastern experiences to build their own startups is unique and is especially eye-opening given how much there is for me to learn.
column23: A technical skill of mine is coding with Java, which I learned in my computer science class. Throughout the past year, I’ve utilized that skill on side projects such as a ski inventory system and an advising site. While I could improve my proficiency, I try to work with my current knowledge. I’d love to strengthen my SQL ability and improve my understanding of machine learning. The term is somewhat of a buzzword, and I want to gain knowledge about how it works rather than hearing about it while lacking understanding. When it comes to learning new things, my biggest motivator is knowing that the work I’m doing will benefit me in the future. I try to make decisions with my end goal in mind, so applying to join Generate is as much a decision about the immediate benefits as it is about the long-term ones. This also connects to my mindset regarding challenges. “Nothing good comes easy” is a motto that’s worked its way into many aspects of my life. Whether through my course load, extracurriculars, or hobbies, I’ve always sought out challenges. There’s something to be said for following through on your commitments and upholding that is an unwavering value of mine-even when it gets tough.
column24: There is lots to learn about data science as a whole; however, this past year I took statistics, which gave me a little insight into what it’s about. One concept I found interesting was linear regression and the least squares method. Taking calculus simultaneously allowed me to learn the “why” and “how” behind the way certain things work-such as understanding that, to get the line of best fit, you are taking partial derivatives of the sum of the errors squared (essentially the first derivative test). Though I don’t consciously think about it, I do believe that style of learning influences my approach to problem solving. Being able to connect the dots between different sets of knowledge makes it easier to complete the whole picture. I would love to be able to speak more technically on what draws me to the Data team; however, I feel that being less familiar is why I wanted to get involved in the first place, and I’m hoping that will serve as a catalyst for my exploration into the field of data science. I’m confident in my ability to adapt and learn based on what’s asked and expected of me, especially when it comes to taking on new things.
column25: Throughout high school, I prioritized partaking in diverse extracurriculars to become more well-rounded and gain insight into what I truly love doing. This taught me the importance of building skills outside your focus. Although you need strong technical skills to become a successful engineer, you also need to be able to communicate effectively, write professionally, and work with others. I aim to continually put myself into new experiences so that I can cast my net wider, which will in turn help me become a better engineer. While participating in clubs helped me grow, starting my own initiatives has impacted me more significantly. A great example is a computer camp I founded. Being responsible for the success of something is an entirely different experience from being a member, and that has given me a complete perspective on teamwork and commitment. It’s this leadership experience where my value of following through on commitments stems from. Having experienced the frustration when team members aren’t fully committed, I ensure I never sign up for something I can’t deliver on. I never want to be the team member who doesn’t pull their weight.
column26: I just want to thank you again for your time and your help with answering my questions earlier this summer!

column22: I am interested in joining Generate specifically because looking aside the opportunity to grow my professional and personal skills, Generate shares my values of being developmental and inclusive. In my past experiences where I was a leader for my peers I had a priority of allowing everyone to feel secure in a safe and growth oriented environment. As a newcomer in Generate, I can feel confident knowing that those who will be leading and guiding me will foster a similar environment allowing me to reach my full potential. I’m looking forward to experiencing that same kind of environment from the other side. Knowing Generate is built on these principles gives me assurance that I’ll be challenged and encouraged in the same way I have done for others.The Generate culture is the one I want to grow in and contribute to.
column23: I have developed Python through competitive programming(USACO and ACSL) and personal projects. One aspect I really enjoy about Python is the ease of use for manipulating data and machine learning in general. However, I would like to develop more front end skills such as Javascript through other projects to deploy more complex web applications that are full stack. This, and the idea of bringing my ideas and visions to fruition is what motivates me to learn new things and take on complex challenges. column24: I really enjoy the theory behind predictive models because they transform raw data into clear takeaways. One approach that’s shaped my thinking is kernel density estimation, which I’ve applied in my NBA shot chart project. By visualizing shot locations and predicting scoring tendencies based on court zones, I’ve learned how powerful data can be when paired with the right tools. This project helped me to understand where a player is most effective and how shot selection impacts performance. It’s made me approach basketball with a more analytical lens and think critically about how to model data effectively. More broadly, it showed me how data science can connect deeply with personal interests, which makes the learning process even more motivating and rewarding. I believe that the most meaningful work happens when I can combine technical skills with the things I’m passionate about through creating solutions that are both insightful and interesting.
column25: I have been a TA for the Mathematics department at Northeastern since January and previously worked as a peer tutor throughout high school. column22: I'm drawn to Generate because it perfectly bridges my dual passions: data science and entrepreneurship. Unlike typical student organizations focused on theoretical projects, Generate works with real startups, giving me invaluable exposure to the entrepreneurial ecosystem I plan to join after graduation. column24: My favorite data science methodology is the Cross-Industry Standard Process for Data Mining (CRISP-DM) framework, which has fundamentally shaped how I approach every project. CRISP-DM's six-phase cycle of business understanding, data understanding, data preparation, modeling, evaluation, and deployment ensures I never jump straight into building models without first understanding the actual problem I'm solving. This methodology was crucial in my European Soccer Scouting Platform project. Instead of immediately scraping data and building algorithms, I first spent time understanding what scouts actually need: identifying undervalued players, not just the highest performers. This business understanding phase led me to focus on market value discrepancies rather than just statistical excellence, making the final product far more valuable. The iterative nature of CRISP-DM has also taught me that data science is rarely linear. In my trading algorithm project, I cycled back from evaluation to data preparation multiple times when I realized my initial feature engineering wasn't capturing market volatility effectively. This framework taught me that "failed" iterations aren't setbacks but essential steps toward better solutions. What I love most about CRISP-DM is its emphasis on deployment and real-world impact, not just model accuracy. This aligns perfectly with Generate's mission of building products that drive actual business outcomes. The methodology ensures I'm always thinking about how my data solutions will be used by real people to make real decisions, which is exactly the mindset needed for Generate's client-focused approach.

column23: One technical skill I’ve developed confidence in is fine-tuning machine learning hyperparameters. I first learned about this in high school while working on a sleep apnea prediction model for the Synopsys Science Fair. There were no step-by-step instructions — just me, StackOverflow, and a lot of trial and error. Over time, I began to understand the deeper logic behind tuning, like how a lower learning rate helps prevent the model from settling in a local minimum in a larger dataset. I also learned that hyperparameters only matter up to a point. Unless you really mess them up, the dataset itself usually has a much bigger impact on performance.  One skill I’m eager to improve is statistical analysis, particularly methods like ANOVA and MANOVA. As someone interested in psychology and behavioral research, I know mastering these tools is essential to finding meaning in complex data and also helps you frame the research questions you ask. What motivates me to take on challenges is the impact I hope to make. I’m driven by the “why” behind what I learn. For example, all my past research projects related to data analysis or machine learning stemmed from my interest in the subject itself, whether that be sleep apnea, transformers (the architecture behind ChatGPT), or studying the emotion of fear.
column24: A methodology that has deeply influenced how I think about data science is the transformer architecture, first introduced in the Attention Is All You Need paper. What struck me most about this work wasn’t just the performance improvements it brought, it was the way it challenged assumptions. By removing recurrence (the mechanism for CNNs and RNNs) and relying entirely on attention, the authors showed that it was possible to now relate words in context with each other over longer ranges — something not possible before! That mindset of questioning the default approach has directly shaped a research project I worked on involving Fourier transforms for audio processing. I was inspired by follow-up work like the FNet, which replaced attention with Fourier-based token mixing. I became curious: if transformers could succeed without recurrence, could they also work without attention? That question led me to explore alternatives in audio processing, using Fourier transforms to pick up patterns across an entire sound clip, while also making the model faster and less resource-intensive to run. That lesson continues to shape how I approach research: by staying open to unconventional ideas and exploring options outside of “industry-standard” or “state-of-the-art” approaches.

column24: One of my favorite data science methodologies is Exploratory Data Analysis, or EDA. It involves using visualizations and statistics to explore a dataset before applying any models. EDA helps uncover trends, patterns, missing values, and relationships between variables. Just as importantly, it can also show what is not present in the data, which can be a valuable insight on its own.  I appreciate EDA because it often reveals unexpected findings. In some cases, the lack of a relationship between two variables has led me to ask better questions or reconsider my assumptions. This approach encourages a deeper understanding of the data, rather than rushing to build a model too quickly.  EDA has shaped the way I approach problem-solving by helping me focus on context, clarity, and curiosity. I use tools like box plots, scatter plots, and correlation heatmaps to get a full picture of the data’s structure. These insights guide how I clean the data, select features, and design my analysis.  Overall, EDA keeps me grounded in the data itself. It helps ensure that any models I build are based on a clear understanding of the problem and the information available.

column23: Much of my statistical and machine learning foundation is based in econometrics, specifically causal inference which is primarily relevant to marketing data science. I’ve developed a strong understanding of incrementality testing which uses experimentation and quasi-experimental methods to measure the true value a marketing decision or channel provides. Causal techniques like randomized control trials, geo-based holdout experiments, or synthetic control methods isolate causal effects from confounding factors providing a clearer picture for marketing decision makers. In contrast to my statistical background, I would like to improve my coding skills, ensuring that it is production level with scalability. Without significant experience coding in a professional space, Generate provides a perfect opportunity to learn from more experienced individuals and meet client facing production standards. column24: Marketing Mix Modeling (MMM) has experienced a renaissance thanks to recent advances in causal machine learning, particularly as privacy regulations limit traditional attribution methods. Modern MMM approaches leverage causal inference techniques to address fundamental questions about media effectiveness that correlation-based models cannot answer. The core challenge in MMM is disentangling the causal impact of different marketing channels from confounding factors like seasonality, external events, and channel interactions. Traditional econometric approaches often struggled with media saturation curves and adstock effects, leading to oversimplified linear assumptions. Recent developments in causal ML have introduced more sophisticated solutions. For example, Bayesian structural time series models, popularized by Google's CausalImpact package, use synthetic control methods to estimate counterfactual scenarios. The shift toward causal ML in MMM is enabling marketers to move from "what happened" to "what would happen if we changed our media strategy," fundamentally transforming budget allocation decisions. This shift from correlation to causation has shaped the way I approach problem solving in my own work. Rather than using the fanciest or hottest technique, I find value in uncovering root causes.
column25: During my first co-op at Scotiabank, I analyzed economic policies and briefed C-suite executives on my findings. This experience sparked my interest in statistical policy analysis, leading me to research causal inference techniques, specifically Difference-in-Differences methods and Synthetic Control Methods. I discovered that many econometric skills transfer directly to marketing data science, and quickly grew interested in uncovering consumer behavior. As I seek a second co-op and map out my early career, I am diving deeper into Marketing Mix Modeling, incrementality testing, and attribution analysis.
