column24: A particular framework which has changed my approach to problem solving is network analysis: representing data as a graph of interconnected nodes.  When approaching a data-driven problem, it’s often easy to oversimplify and fail to capture the nuance in the process. When applying techniques such as regression that you’ve used day in and day out, it’s easy not to question the routine assumptions of independence and randomness.  Network analysis forces you to drop these comfortable assumptions. Rather than looking at data points individually, the entire set becomes a single, dynamic & interconnected web. An individual is no longer just a row of metadata, but instead a product of its neighbors which can be extracted using algorithms such as community detection. Outliers identified through clustering analysis become crucial bottlenecks and hub-points which challenge the robustness of your techniques. This became clear working on a project analyzing GitHub contributor data. After hours spent with traditional neural networks and bayesian models, a single network plot divulged the underlying relationships driving collaboration behavior between users.  As a whole, the mindset change required by this paradigm has led me to approach my problem-solving through a more holistic lens. I leave my pre-conceived notions at the door, and consider new challenges as opportunities for exploration. I believe that this will enable me to mesh well with the interdisciplinary focus of Generate, which uses elements of software engineering, data science, hardware design, and marketing to ensure the most effective outcomes for its clients.
column25: My professional and extracurricular experiences have equipped me to tackle problem-solving with agility and rigor. As the Flight Software Lead for the satellite development program at Northeastern, I was faced with the task of developing image compression algorithms for our satellite. The constrained hardware environment, combined with countless risks of the space environment, would have ordinarily led development to slow to a standstill. Using these constraints as signposts, I dissected the problem to identify opportunities for improvement. Rather than implementing arduous hardware testing, implementing simulated packet losses helped establish points of failure and shortlist viable models. These considerations resulted in a more effective outcome at a significantly faster pace.   As a co-op at MORSE, I was tasked with improving a data pipeline responsible for millions of data points per minute. Uncovering a bottleneck which greatly increased processing times, I had the solution of separating the pipeline into separate jobs. While unorthodox, this proved to solve the issue while greatly improving maintainability and the ease of future development.  These outcomes have taught me that efficiency isn’t just about following a standard procedure. It’s about taking existing assumptions and processes, and turning them upside down. I believe that Generate, with its focus on impactful innovation, understands this concept better than anyone.

column22: I’m interested in joining Generate because it aligns heavily with both my academic background and my professional goals. Further, I’m enthusiastic about learning from my peers, who I’m confident will bring different strengths and perspectives. column23: One technical skill I am confident in is creating data visualizations using Python, specifically with Matplotlib and Seaborn. column24: One of my favorite data science tools and methodologies is GeoPandas, a Python library that utilizes data science for spatial visualization. While it’s not an algorithm in the traditional sense, GeoPandas acts as a powerful framework for working with geographic data, allowing me to explore a whole new sector of data analysis and compelling visualizations. I first used GeoPandas in an assignment to classify and visualize temperature data across the United States. Watching the visualization come together was exciting and rewarding. The experience helped me understand how incorporating geographic context can reveal additional hidden patterns and insights in a conventional analysis. Moving forward from that assignment, the use of GeoPandas inspired the work of my final project in the class, which analyzed traffic patterns in New York along with external factors which could affect these patterns. GeoPandas as a tool shaped my problem solving approach by encouraging me to think beyond tabular data. In the future, I would love to work on a project analyzing how location influences different trends and behaviors and how that would apply to marketing.  I’ve broadened how I formulate questions, helping me find deeper insights through combining traditional and spatial data methods.
column25: Although I have not been a member of Generate before, my extracurricular experiences have significantly shaped my approach to collaboration, leadership, and adaptability. column22: I’m interested in joining Generate specifically because of the wide range of opportunities you present to all majors. Many clubs focus on specifically giving experience to computer science or business majors only, but this club collectively tries to bring data scientists, engineers, software developers, finance/business majors, and managers together to collaborate. People can thrive the strongest in these environments because they’re always challenged by differing perspectives and ultimately the end product that has tangible impact. Additionally, the description for the Data Scientist role stood out, specifically how it focuses on “implementing data solutions, building dashboards, machine learning, and pipelines that tell stories and drive impact.” That specific part of the description felt like it was describing the exact skills I used in my latest project – a cricket analytics project where I designed a hybrid prediction model using custom weighting and XGBoost, backtested it over multiple decades of data with high accuracy, and visualized these predicted projections by creating interactive and user-friendly dashboards. I also created a backend API to help dynamically filter the front end of the dashboard, making the interface more convenient for users. This taught me how to bring together modeling, backend logic, and storytelling into one user-friendly tool, which is something I know aligns with Generate’s goals. That’s why the Data Scientist role at Generate is a natural fit for my technical background. It would be extremely cool if my drive to produce user-friendly data products and love for turning raw data into something significant would help contribute to a cross functional team like Generate.
column23: One technical skill that I’ve developed and am extremely confident in is my fluency in pandas and my manipulation in dataframes. My fluency in SQL helps with this because I’m able to tie the two skills together to query and transform the data effectively. That’s why I seek out opportunities where I’m pushed to improve and why I’m excited by roles like Generate where learning and collaboration are the core of every product.
column24: While there’s many more advanced ones, my favorite data science methodology is exploratory data analysis because it’s the first moment of the project where a data analyst gets to truly interact with the data. This step is very crucial because it sets the foundation for multiple important decisions and observations to follow such as the feasibility of the data (whether you have missing data and multiple outliers), which variables interact well with one another, and how to take the project forward given the behavior of each variable. Understanding these steps will elevate your analytical skills and will let you have full control over which future steps seem correct. In my own work, especially the recent cricket analytics project, I followed those steps, and it played a massive role in the success of it. At first, my goal of the project was to just create a dashboard for the top 15 batters in cricket history. However, after graphing some basic time series plots and slicing the data up by format, country, and career stage, I realized there was a massive pattern across all batters: they generally share a semi parabolic curve trend in their batting average over a span of their career. This insight excited me, and motivated me to create a prediction algorithm to predict the number of runs a batter will score in 5 years, using this form curve as a key weightage. Without a deep EDA analysis on my end, I never would’ve been able to interact with the data that deeply and never had the vision to take the project as far as I did. It has taught me to slow down and ask thoughtful questions before jumping into technical solutions immediately. It’s shown me that good data science doesn’t immediately start with advanced algorithms, it starts with exploration and key observations.
column25: My extracurricular experiences from high school have shaped me to be the man I am today, especially varsity swimming. Through swimming, I learnt the hard way by having a poor start to my senior year season, where I wasn’t putting in enough effort in the beginning and our team was slowly going down the New Jersey high school swim rankings. However, as captain and a key swimmer, I realized the importance of the role, and swam my heart out every practice since, led the team with conviction, and helped us place second in counties, where I clocked my best 100 butterfly time. This wouldn’t have been possible without our collective efforts and I’m so glad that I was able to have a positive impact on my team. That experience taught me how there will be many ups and downs throughout your journey as an athlete or human, but the most improved ones are the ones who consistently show up to practice and have the resolve to keep pushing themselves no matter the situation. It’s okay to have a below average swim meet, it’s a part of life, but it’s not okay to not learn from those and stay stagnant. We must keep improving ourselves everyday to become the best versions of ourselves. That mindset shapes me to stay dedicated, accountable, and consistent in whatever activity I pursue, helping create a positive impact on the whatever team I’m in.

column24: My favourite data science influential figure is Andrew Ng. If you do not know who he is, Andrew Ng is the founder of Coursera and DeepLearning.AI. Both of these are open-source platforms where anyone can learn about data science without any prerequisites or applications. Andrew Ng is the first person to help me effectively learn ML and AI in a simple way. He is able to break down complicated concepts into shorter, easily digestible sections. What I like about Andrew Ng isn't his technical expertise, as there are many out there with the same skillset. I like his ability to teach and his focus on implementation over pure theory. His advice to "start with a simple model and iterate" has become central to my problem-solving approach. This philosophy from Andrew Ng has shaped how I tackle projects. For example, instead of immediately jumping to complex neural networks for my ML projects, I now begin with simpler models to establish baselines and truly understand the data. In a recent project predicting Taylor Swift song popularity, I started with linear regression before moving to more sophisticated methods. Starting this simple-to-complicated approach for my projects has helped me understand the data better and speed up the development process.

column24: One data science methodology I really value is data visualization. I believe that visualizing data is key to understanding complex patterns and communicating findings clearly. Proper data visualization turns complex data into clear and compelling stories. By using the right charts and visuals, it helps highlight trends, patterns, and relationships that might be hidden in rows of numbers.  In many of my projects, I’ve used tools like Matplotlib and Seaborn to create charts and graphs that reveal trends, correlations, and outliers that might be missed in raw numbers alone. For example, during my analysis of public school data, I developed multi dimensional visualizations that showed how teacher experience and student demographics affected academic performance. These visuals not only helped me draw clearer conclusions but also made it easier to share my findings with others, including those without a technical background. This approach has shaped the way I work by always reminding me to think beyond just numbers and code. I focus on how to present data clearly so that insights are understandable and actionable for a wide audience. When I solve problems, I make sure to explore different ways of visualizing data to uncover hidden patterns or unexpected trends. Ultimately, it encourages me to be both analytical and creative in how I approach data challenges.
column25: When I started my internship at Kloze AI, I was thrown into a fast paced environment where I quickly learned that real world coding is not just about writing perfect programs it is about problem solving and collaboration. column22: I am drawn to Generate’s collaboration in an interdisciplinary space and its tangible impact in an endeavour that is both client-facing and student-serving. column23: One technical strength I’m confident is in algorithmic thinking, especially when applied to data problems. I enjoy reducing large, complex datasets into meaningful vectorized pipelines, efficient SQL queries or logical design for data transformation. I like being able to map a solution from idea to actual implementation.   What I want to get better at is applying that logic to messier, real-world data problems. I’ve mostly worked with structured, curated datasets or academic datasets. I would definitely like more experience with noisy or incomplete data, build robust pipelines that are adaptable to change, and make considerations on deployment and scalability. I am concerned about my lack of exposure to interesting or real-world data that doesn’t necessarily make sense at first. It’s something I’m getting to learn at my co-op, and am hoping to learn more with time!   I’m motivated by the desire to extract clarity out of chaos. I find joy in deriving structure from murky problems and using my curiosity as a tool to see the bigger picture. I enjoy the challenge of seeing how effective the data can be in filling in the gaps and completing the story.
column24: My favourite algorithm is the Gale-Shapley algorithm for the stable-matching problem, a fundamental concept in graph theory and economics. It provides a clean, simple procedure to match two groups based on submitted preferences, guaranteeing stable and optimal matching on one group’s perspective. It encourages me to seek clarity and reiterates to me that “complex problems often have simple solutions that are overlooked.” It’s quite elegant logic paired with powerful real-world applications, like assigning medical students to residencies or matching students in a club to teams/projects based on their interests : )  Leo Breiman left academia to pursue poetry and he returned, only to revolutionize machine learning through predictive models (he invented Random Forests!). I admire his courage to challenge traditional beliefs in statistics and his focus on practical results over theoretical hypotheticals. His work really pushes me to embrace complexity and not be afraid to take the most bizarre, unconventional route to arrive at a solution worth getting to. He also says to embrace the complexity and messiness of data.   I suppose I just really appreciate the dichotomy of data. That balance between simplicity and complexity, that’s what makes it interesting, intellectually rigorous, but at the same time, deeply human.
column25: In my two years at Northeastern, my experiences have spanned research, teaching and internships, and span several domains. column24: K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) was one of the first algorithms I learned in DS2001, and it marked the beginning of my interest in the field. I was frustrated with the lack of technicality in my Psychology classes, so I decided on a whim to take DS2000, thinking that it would help supplement my research skills. In actuality, it began my love for data science, and I actually began to enjoy my DS classwork more than my psychology classwork. KNN was my first experience building a model that could make predictions based on real data, and seeing it work, even in a simple binary classification, was exciting. It taught me that even the most basic tools can be powerful when applied thoughtfully, and also that most of the work in data science comes from preprocessing, not building the actual model. That idea has stuck with me as I’ve taken on new challenges in data science: the actual solutions are relatively simple, but it’s important to be detail-oriented and careful in the preparation stages.
column25: My first year at Northeastern was largely shaped by my two main out-of-class commitments: working in a research lab, and Chinese Student Association. A lot of my professional and academic growth developed from my hands-on experience in psychology research. Most of my social life, however, came from CSA and PAAC (Pan-Asian American Council) at Northeastern. Within PAAC, I found so many people who were similar to me, both socially and academically. We loved to do the same things, like get food together, and many of us also had similar work ethics and ambitions. After serving on the eboard last year and this upcoming year, I’ve learned a lot about how to connect with people, how to bridge communities (especially strengthening eboard-to-general-member connections), and the importance of communication and proactivity in organizations.

column24: One of the most influential figures in data science for me is Geoffrey Hinton, the father of modern neural networks. Besides his groundbreaking contributions to deep learning, I admire his decision to use his platform to warn the world about the ethical and societal risks of AI, such as its potential role in misinformation, cybercrime, and autonomous weaponry.  Hinton’s perspective really shaped how I approach data science and product development. His warnings influenced my belief that innovation should be guided by thoughtful intention and social responsibility. This recently inspired a research project of mine and a friend’s, where I looked into whether AI can construct sound theories or detect misinformation when provided with both relevant and irrelevant data. Through it, I explored how machine learning does in solving complex problems, while also confronting its limitations around morality, bias, and human emotion. (sorry, I put in the wrong response for this in my last submission! I understand if it cannot be accepted, I hope you'll understand!)

column23: I am most confident in exploratory data analysis with Python, where I clean messy datasets, pull patterns with pandas and NumPy, and back findings with solid statistical checks. column24: Leo Breiman’s work on random forests shapes how I approach predictive modeling. I like the way the ensemble handles complex interactions and guards against overfitting through bootstrapped sampling and out of bag error checks. When I built a volunteer no show predictor for a food pantry, a random forest baseline captured nonlinear relationships that logistic regression overlooked and raised recall from sixty to eighty percent. The project taught me to favor flexible models with built in validation and to keep my pipeline honest with rigorous out of sample testing.
column25: Although I haven’t joined Generate yet, an experience in my California hometown shaped my growth as both a developer and a teammate. I led a small student crew to build a lightweight scheduling site and integrated Twilio texts that ping volunteers 24 hours before their shift. The no-show rate dropped from about 40 percent to under 15, and weekly distributions finally ran on time. Turning a community headache into a tested, documented, and hand-off-ready tool taught me that code only matters when it delivers real results for real people.

column24: Gradient Boosting really captures how I approach complex problem-solving because of its iterative improvement methodology that mirrors how effective learning actually works. Instead of trying to build one perfect model, Gradient Boosting creates a sequence of models where each new one learns from and corrects the mistakes of the previous ones. This has taught me to value continuous refinement and adaptive learning over trying to get everything right immediately. This methodology has shaped how I tackle analytical challenges by encouraging me to see errors and suboptimal results as learning opportunities rather than failures. During my research with Transformer algorithms, I applied this thinking when optimizing model architectures—systematically identifying areas of poor performance and developing targeted improvements through hyperparameter tuning rather than starting over with each iteration. What makes Gradient Boosting particularly valuable is its focus on learning from mistakes and its ability to handle complex, non-linear relationships in data while still providing interpretability through feature importance analysis. This iterative improvement mindset is crucial for client work because it enables systematic refinement based on feedback and changing requirements. The methodology's emphasis on continuous learning and adaptation corresponds with Generate's collaborative approach, where solutions evolve through ongoing dialogue with clients rather than being delivered as static, one-time outputs.
column25: My research and analytics experiences have really shaped how I understand the connection between technical rigor and practical impact. Working in real estate analytics was particularly eye-opening because it showed me how data-driven insights create measurable business value. These experiences have fundamentally shaped how I approach technical challenges, not as isolated problems to solve, but as opportunities to create meaningful value for real people and organizations. column24: In data science, it's easy to chase the newest model or algorithm, but the methodology that’s shaped me most is HITL learning. At its core, HITL emphasizes collaboration between humans and machines, reminding us that AI doesn’t have to be a black box; it can be a dialogue. There’s a lot of fear surrounding AI: fears of job loss, of ethical failures, or of machines replacing human judgment. I believe the best way to ease that fear is by building tools that put people at the center of the loop. When I used HITL frameworks to refine LLM-based interview tools or improve data quality in policy research, it wasn’t just about accuracy; it was about trust. When users can shape a system, they’re more likely to understand it, adopt it, and see its value. This philosophy now guides my approach to every project. I don’t just want to build something that works; I want to build something people believe in. HITL reminds me that data science should be empowering, not intimidating. That’s the kind of work I want to keep doing, bridging the gap between fear and functionality, and showing how AI can make our lives better, not harder.
column25: While I haven’t been a part of Generate yet, my experiences so far have taught me the value of building with purpose and building with people. column24: My favorite data science methodology is the Ant Colony Optimization (ACO) algorithm, not just because I implemented it to solve my high school's bus routing problem, but because it fundamentally changed how I approach complex optimization challenges. ACO mimics how ants collectively find the shortest path to food sources through pheromone trails, demonstrating that simple rules can emerge into sophisticated solutions. This nature-inspired approach taught me that the best solutions often come from understanding the problem's inherent structure rather than forcing rigid frameworks. When I applied ACO to redesign our school's bus routes, achieving a 14% reduction in travel time, I learned that sometimes unconventional methods yield breakthrough results. ACO has shaped my problem-solving philosophy: start simple, iterate constantly, and let patterns emerge from the data. In my current USPTO research, I apply this mindset by first understanding the natural networks of collaboration before imposing complex models. Rather than immediately jumping to advanced neural networks, I build incrementally, just as ants strengthen successful paths over time. This methodology reminds me that data science isn't just about applying the latest algorithms; it's about choosing the right tool for the right problem. Sometimes, inspiration from a colony of ants can revolutionize how an entire community commutes.
column25: My professional and extracurricular experiences have shaped me into someone who thrives at the intersection of technical innovation and community impact. column24: One data science methodology that stood out to me during my MISM course last semester was K-means clustering. It was one of the first times I saw how unsupervised learning could uncover hidden patterns in large datasets without any predefined labels. We applied it to segment users based on behavioral data, and seeing how the algorithm grouped similar users by minimizing intra-cluster variance completely changed how I thought about data analysis. Rather than jumping straight to assumptions or predefined categories, I started approaching problems by first exploring how the data naturally clusters and what those patterns reveal.  K-means taught me the value of letting the data speak, which has shaped the way I frame questions and extract insights, especially when working with large or ambiguous datasets in SQL or Excel. It showed me that strong analysis is not just about running numbers but about asking thoughtful questions, exploring creatively, and interpreting findings in context. This approach continues to influence how I solve problems and work through real-world scenarios.

column24: One of my favorite data science methodologies is Principal Component Analysis (PCA). I have learned about its technical utility in reducing dimensions, and also the general mindset it promotes about creating clarity from complexity without losing the bigger picture. In data analysis, it is easy to get overwhelmed by complexity and high-dimensional datasets, but there are ways to create simplicity without erasing meaning from your work. Learning about PCA and its technical applications also taught me a new mindset I could use while working with others.  When creating a dashboard or sharing data with others, my goal is always to simplify information as much as needed for my client’s knowledge level without sacrificing the parts that matter most. PCA has taught me that compression can create clarity in chaos without losing the bigger picture, which is especially relevant in client-facing roles, where I have worked within Generate, co-ops, and other extracurriculars I am a part of.  PCA has shaped the way I think about problem-solving by encouraging me to think about truly understanding the whole, then identifying the most important pieces and drowning out the noise. This has helped me to be a better teacher and communicator, especially towards clients with less technical knowledge.
column25: Being part of Generate has been one of the most formative experiences of my time at Northeastern. column24: The data science methodology that’s influenced me the most is CRISP‑DM. This was always the way I worked through those phases in my projects, even before I knew the methodology had a name. I always started with understanding the problem, then collecting and preparing the data, building something that works, and finally delivering it so people can actually use it.  I saw this play out in the Personal Portfolio Manager, where we had to figure out what insights users needed first, then design an AWS‑based pipeline to clean and store their data before running any analysis. The process was exactly the same in my RAG system project. We start by understanding the question, preparing the text data, choosing the right retrieval setup, and finally making sure the output was meaningful.  What I like about CRISP‑DM is that it gives structure without being too rigid. This not only prevents me from coding before I’ve nailed down the problem, but it also reminds me that delivering something useful is just as important as building something technically impressive. That approach has shaped how I tackle every data project: methodically, but with room to adapt as I go.
column25: My professional and extracurricular experiences have set me up to thrive in a collaborative, fast‑moving environment like Generate. As a Backend Software Engineer for Northeastern’s Student Government Association, I worked on a TypeScript and NestJS system for nominations and application tracking, plus an internal attendance manager in Next.js and Prisma, making sure everything was reliable by thoroughly testing changes before deployment. In NU‑CLEAR, a co‑op feedback platform, I built a Python and Flask REST API with MySQL, deployed in Docker, so users could filter and analyze feedback in real time. In Catalyst, I wrote algorithms to turn complex degree audits into clear, actionable guidance for students. These projects taught me how to take messy requirements and turn them into scalable, maintainable solutions while working closely with teammates. I’ve learned that the best solutions come from rapid iteration, openness to feedback, and genuine collaboration, values I’m ready to bring to Generate while continuing to grow as a software engineer.

column22: Generate has been to me one of the most well-rounded student organizations at Northeastern, combining technical rigor, real-world product development, and a close-knit, supportive community. After attending many social and technical events over my last semesters, I’ve always been consistently impressed by the creativity and collaborative spirit of its members and the energy of everyone in the club. Regardless if you’re in Community or Data, everyone is welcoming and working toward the same cause - making sure that the members of Generate are growing and learning from each other. Even with directors and chiefs who may seem distant, they aren’t - this strong sense of connection and inclusion remains central to how Generate operates. Generate is special because it allows members to immerse themselves in an environment that makes learning and being career driven a reward because you spend time working on a challenging and meaningful project with teammates that eventually become close friends. And when Showcase rolls around, it highlights the best of what we do in Generate - seeing every team's hard work and creativity. It’s a reminder of how much you can accomplish with talented people who become both colleagues and friends.
column23: One technical skill I am confident in is data manipulation using SQL and Python. I have experience handling large datasets, performing complex queries, and transforming data to extract meaningful insights, directly supporting business decisions in my current co-op. In the meantime, I want to tap into deep learning with TensorFlow/PyTorch to tackle complex healthcare problems like medical image analysis and predictive health. The ability of deep learning to uncover hidden patterns in messy, unstructured data can go beyond what traditional methods can achieve. I’m excited to further explore this in my Machine Learning II course in the Spring, where I'll strengthen both mathematical and practical foundations in ML. I’ve always been motivated to power innovative solutions for preventative care, even as a non healthcare professional. I figured out early on that data science could be my way of making a meaningful impact. Using a combination of creativity and problem-solving in data science that requires both ability to build accurate models and storytelling to drive real-world action always keeps me constantly engaged.
column24: One of my favorite data science algorithms is Principal Component Analysis because of the way it handles dimensionality while still preserving meaningful patterns. The first time I ever attempted  to understand it was when I was working on analyzing gene expression matrices to identify marker genes. From there, I was intrigued by the math behind being able to transform more than a thousand features into a couple of principal components without losing information in what appears to be untouchable data. Yet, it somehow can be as interpretable in a simple elbow plot. Using PCA as an example, I approach problem solving in a way to simplify complexity without losing signal in the midst of messy and complex data. When working with manipulating thousands of database records, loaded with nulls, unknowns, and hundreds of attributes, I apply a similar mindset; I sift through the noise to uncover meaningful patterns in the data that would have gotten lost, enabling cleaner and effective modeling and analysis.
column25: Being on the first ever data client team, I know first hand how  complex and unpredictable working with a client can be. Yet despite all the obstacles the team and I faced during the semester, we managed to deliver a product we were proud of. I learned how to collaborate with a stakeholder, adapt to limitations (like working solely with Google Sheets), and quickly pivot/troubleshoot (like switching to Google Sheets API). Despite all that, showing up in the corner room of the Sherm after a long day of co-op and still being able to laugh -even while pumping out a few more lines of code - was one of the most rewarding parts of my week.   Two semesters later, I’m still extremely close to those who I’ve formed connections with on my time as an Events coordinator, and even more so the amazing people who I worked with on Eatwell. Even then, I loved meeting people in other branches/fields that I normally never get to see as a data science major. Generate played a pivotal role in my third year, and I’m eager to continue building those meaningful experiences into my fourth year.

column23: One technical skill I’ve developed and feel confident in is data querying and backend integration. While interning at Acadia, I redesigned PostgreSQL queries that supported Power BI dashboards for major financial institutions, reducing run times by 99%. I’ve since built on that experience through backend development at ZOR!, where I designed REST APIs to handle real-time health and environmental data from iOS devices. column24: My favorite data science methodology is dynamic programming because it perfectly reflects how I love breaking down complex problems into simpler, manageable parts. Dynamic programming solves problems by dividing them into overlapping subproblems and building solutions step-by-step, avoiding redundant work. This efficient approach aligns with my passion for solving technical puzzles in AI and engineering.  For example, Hidden Markov Models, which are widely used in sequence modeling and prediction, rely on dynamic programming algorithms like Viterbi to find the most probable hidden states efficiently. Similarly, Constraint Satisfaction Problems also use dynamic programming in order to break down large search spaces into constrained smaller problems making them solvable.  I apply this mindset broadly in my work to understand problem structure, refine better solutions, and optimize through mistakes and feedback. Dynamic programming has shaped the way I approach problems by encouraging efficient, scalable solutions. This approach motivates me to deliver impactful results and fits well with Generate’s mission of combining innovation and real world problem solving.
column25: While I haven’t been in Generate yet, many of my experiences mirror its mission of building real solutions through collaboration and iteration. column22: What draws me to Generate is the unique mix of technical creativity and strong sense of community. column23: One technical skill I'm confident in is building forecasting models by identifying and developing the most impactful features. During my co-op, I created a student enrollment model that went beyond our historical data. I explored the enrollment pipeline to identify the strongest predictors, performed exploratory data analysis, and ran correlation tests to hypothesize new features that may influence enrollment, such as F1 visa wait times. Through the iterative exploration and hypothesis testing, I created a custom yield rate methodology that led to 77% model accuracy. One skill I want to improve on is fine-tuning models. There is always room to maximize performance, so I want to explore new modeling techniques, such as model stacking, and learn how to apply different tuning strategies, and better understand how each adjustment impacts accuracy.  What motivates me to take on challenges is my curiosity. I’m driven by the desire to understand how processes work and uncover patterns that shape outcomes. For example, that mindset led me to investigate the potential link between F1 visa wait times and enrollment. For me, learning is most meaningful when it starts with questions I genuinely care about and that curiosity keeps me motivated to explore open-ended problems.
column24: The data science methodology that shaped my work is CRISP-DM (Cross-Industry Standard Process for Data Mining). Three takeaways that continue to guide me are: starting with a deep understanding of the business, iterating across stages to refine assumptions, and planning for long-term model usability. I was introduced to CRISP-DM by a co-worker during my co-op, where I was tasked to build a student enrollment forecasting model. Instead of diving into historical data, I spent a month meeting with teams to understand the enrollment process and define the business problem. Only then did I begin exploring data, running correlation tests, and identifying key variables. As I iterated through data understanding and preparation, I revised my hypotheses and re-tested features.  Finally, it’s easy to assume a model is complete if it’s accurate. However, it’s important to plan for model maintenance. That’s why I created documentions, walkthroughs and updated systems to ensure the model remains usable after my co-op. These three takeaways reshaped how I approach problems. I now prioritize understanding the business context before touching the data, iterate consistently to refine predictors and always document my work. This mindset helps me not only chase accuracy but design solutions for longevity.
column25: Last semester, I participated in Finnovate, where my team developed ClaimCrisis, a startup idea designed to help families file insurance claims after natural disasters. We started as a team of five, but within four weeks we became a team of three. I knew I had to push myself, take on new responsibilities like task tracking, and help restructure how we worked to keep the project alive. What shaped me wasn’t just our product but how we adapted together. We juggled multiple tasks, from reaching out to nonprofit organizations to insurance research. Our ideas shifted multiple times as we uncovered gaps, which required us to stay flexible and open to change. These experiences taught me that adaptability isn’t just about adjusting your workflow but also your mindset. When we faced setbacks, it was choosing to stay positive, trusting each other, and embracing the uncertainty that pushed our work forward. This project stretched me beyond what I was used to. It challenged me to lead in unfamiliar situations, take initiative, and stay open to changes. ClaimCrisis became a reminder to me that growth happens when I’m uncomfortable and that some of the most fun and rewarding experiences come from facing challenges.

column24: One of the most influential figures in data science for me is Julia Silge. Her work, especially in making complex concepts in natural language processing and statistical modeling more accessible, has shaped how I approach learning and problem-solving. Through her contributions to the tidytext package and her open content, she shows us that data science is not as intimidating as you think. What stands out most for me is her ability to clearly communicate both the how and the why behind methodologies. I have learned that teaching is one of the best ways to truly know something, and that mindset has made me more thoughtful in my own work. Whether I am exploring a new topic or working on a project, I try to break things down clearly and always seek the deeper reasoning behind the data so I can explain it to others as well.

column24: I think that dimensionality reductions (and the manifold hypothesis more generally) have shaped my perspective by making me more aware of the trap of trying to include too many variables. It’s been known for a long time that simple models with less parameters generalize bette, despite this there is a tendency to want to include more things in models as we learn more about the systems we are studying and understand of more effects/forces that could impact results we include more parameters into our models to improve accuracy. The thing is most of said parameters are not important, and especially in biological systems where there are so many possible interactions its important to find a way to remove the unnecessary components not only for pragmatic reasons like ease of implementation but because these smaller models actually do generalise better.
column25: I think that my time at Sanofi has shaped me greatly by also reinforcing some of the ideas I have from dimensionality reduction. My work involved developing an assay (a kind of test) to determine certain properties of our process. I had to systematically control and understand the effect of a variety of different variables and I often found the greatest success (not just immediate but also the most generalisable) in the most limited scenarios with the least amount of free variables. I think that even though we have a great understanding of some of these systems the noise that arises when we include more variables can create a lot of uncertainty, and I take that “incrementalist” approach to many problems.

column24: One of the most influential figures I’ve encountered in the data science space is Allie Miller. I first heard her speak at a Break Through Tech AI event, and her talk had a lasting impact on how I think about the field. Allie’s background showed me how multifaceted a career in AI and data science can be. What stood out to me most was how she emphasized the importance of not just building intelligent systems, but building them responsibly and with a strong understanding of both business and user impact. Her ability to bridge deep technical expertise with real-world applications and policy influence helped me realize that data science isn’t just about models and metrics. It's also about communication, scale, and ethical responsibility. Hearing her speak motivated me to be more intentional about the problems I work on, and to approach data science as a tool for creating scalable, human-centered solutions. It also encouraged me to think more about how I communicate technical ideas, how I can contribute to cross-functional teams, and how I can grow into a well-rounded, impact-driven data scientist.

column24: I really like the logistic regression algorithm because it's a very simple algorithm, but it is so effective in many different scenarios. It’s easily one of the most useful and versatile algorithms in data science, and is the foundation for a lot of machine learning and more advanced algorithms as well. It makes me think about how the simplest solutions can sometimes be the best. Whenever I try to solve a problem, I always look for the simplest solution first and then try to fine-tune or modify it as needed. In my role as planning and scheduling coordinator for Aaroh, I had to find a way to track our members’ attendance. In my first semester in the position, I wrote down the time that everyone was expected to be at practice in the notes app on my phone, which was the simplest solution I could think of. This approach was effective, but I improved it further in the next semester. I started tracking attendance on a google sheet, which provided much more versatile tracking and actually allowed me to enforce other rules more effectively.
column25: For the past year, I served as planning and scheduling coordinator of NU Aaroh, a music club at Northeastern. In this role, I was responsible for ensuring our events ran smoothly, which ironically taught me that something will inevitably go wrong at any event. I learned that the best way to deal with a problem like this is to maintain my composure to find methodical solutions. This ability to stay calm under pressure directly applies to client work at Generate, where meeting deadlines and managing client relationships require the same level-headed approach to problem-solving. This role also taught me the importance of planning ahead. Last year, our leadership team frequently found ourselves scrambling to finalize event details at the last minute. Now, as president of Aaroh, I’m learning from my experience and have implemented a system where we plan the majority of our semester in advance. My experience as a leader in Aaroh has helped me become more organized, intentional and confident.

column24: It's no secret how influential artificial intelligence has become in all disciplines, especially computer and data science. Ashish Vaswani is regarded as one of the godfathers of modern AI through his groundbreaking work on transformer technology. Through his research, he demonstrated how a more focused approach with simpler architectures could outperform their more powerful and complex counterparts. What really resonates with me about Vaswani's breakthrough is how it challenged everything we thought we knew about processing sequential data. His team didn't just tweak existing methods. They completely rethought the problem and showed that paying attention to what matters most could beat brute force complexity. Sometimes I feel the urge to build the most cutting-edge and complex solution because it feels cool and exciting. But Vaswani's work reminds me to ask what's the simplest approach that could actually work here? In my own projects, I've started applying this mindset by focusing on the key signals that drive results rather than getting lost in elaborate pipelines. Just as he proved, a simpler and more targeted approach can achieve fantastic results while being more efficient and maintainable.

column24: One concept in data science that really stuck with me is active learning. I came across it while building a resume screening tool at InstaLily AI, and it completely changed how I thought about training models. The tool was designed to help hiring teams prioritize top candidates by ranking resumes based on experience, relevance, and domain fit. Early on, I realized we didn’t just need more data,  we needed smarter ways to decide which resumes were most valuable to label and learn from. That’s when I started exploring active learning. Instead of feeding the model a giant labeled dataset, I built a loop that identified the resumes it was most uncertain about, then sent those to human reviewers for feedback. This made the model better, faster, and way more efficient over time. It showed me how important it is to work with your data, not just throw more of it at the problem. Active learning helped me approach machine learning like a conversation: you ask questions, learn from the answers, and get better with every round. That mindset has stuck with me in every project since, and it's why I love this space so much.
